CLEAN THE DATA<a name=clean></a>¶

As is almost always the case, the next step is to clean the corpus. Note that the order in which the cleaning steps are performed may affect the final form of the cleaned corpus.

In the case of spam detection, can you think of some reasons why you might not want to be too drastic with the cleaning stage?

In [10]:
# Function to clean the corpus
clean_corpus <- function(corpus){
  corpus <- tm_map(corpus, content_transformer(replace_abbreviation))
  corpus <- tm_map(corpus, removePunctuation)
  corpus <- tm_map(corpus, removeNumbers)
  corpus <- tm_map(corpus, stemDocument)
  corpus <- tm_map(corpus, content_transformer(tolower))
  corpus <- tm_map(corpus, stripWhitespace)
  corpus <- tm_map(corpus, removeWords, c(stopwords("en"))) 
    return(corpus)
}

SMS.corpus.clean <- clean_corpus(SMS.corpus)

We can also identify document-specific high-information terms using the tf-idf weighting.

In [14]:
SMS_words <- ham.spam %>% 
  unnest_tokens(word,Msg) %>% 
  count(SpamOrHam,word, sort=TRUE) %>% 
  ungroup()

SMS_distinctive <- SMS_words %>% 
  bind_tf_idf(word,SpamOrHam,n) %>% 
  arrange(desc(tf_idf)) %>% 
  mutate(word = factor(word, levels = rev(unique(word)))) %>%
  group_by(SpamOrHam) %>% 
  top_n(15,tf_idf) %>% 
  ungroup()

TRAINING/TESTING DATA<a name=ttd></a>¶

Classifiers need to be trained on a subset of the data and tested/evaluated on the complement to avoid overfitting the model. There's no steadfast rule, but a 70%/30% split is often applied.

In [15]:
ind = sample(1:nrow(ham.spam), size=0.7*nrow(ham.spam))

ham.spam.train.labels <- ham.spam[ind,]$SpamOrHam
ham.spam.test.labels <- ham.spam[-ind,]$SpamOrHam

We can verify that the training/testing sets are representative (in terms of the target labels).

In [16]:
prop.table(table(ham.spam.train.labels))

We also need to select the features (in this case, terms) to include in the model (otherwise, there'd be too much information to consider). We can use the list of all terms that appear at least 10 times in the training messages, for instance (another approach could be to remove sparse terms).

In [19]:
spam.train = subset(ham.spam[ind,], SpamOrHam == "spam")
ham.train = subset(ham.spam[ind,], SpamOrHam == "ham")

We also need to categorize the features so that the data can be fed into a Naive Bayes classifier. Here, the absence of a frequent term in a SMS message is denoted by "No", while it's presence is denoted by "Yes".

In [22]:
yes.no <- function(x){
    y <- ifelse(x>0,1,0)
    y <- factor(y,levels=c(0,1),labels=c("No","Yes"))
    return(y)
}

NAIVE BAYES CLASSIFIER<a name=nbc></a>¶

We can now apply the naiveBayes function (from library e1071). Notice the syntax: we apply naiveBayes to the training data SMS.train (see above), and the target variable is ham/spam labels in the training subset (ham.spam.train.labels). The laplace=1 option instructs naiveBayes to look "a little bit harder" into the data, while the CV=10 option selects 10 cross-validations.

In [24]:
SMS.classifier.NB <- naiveBayes(SMS.train,ham.spam.train.labels,laplace=1,CV=10) # laplace=1: dig down

SUPPORT VECTOR MACHINES<a name=svm></a>¶

We can use other classifiers - e1071 also implements svm (support vector machines). The principle is the same, although we do not need to first categorize the features (as in NBC).

Can you figure out the syntax? Ignore the parameter type for now.

The cost is related to the price of allowing misclassifications: higher cost values attempt to minimize such misclassifications, but the resulting model tends to lead to overfitting (a littel flexibility in re: misclassfications is a good thing in the long run).

There is some evidence to suggest that the choice of the "linear" kernel is preferable when dealing with text data (as opposed to gaussian for some numerical data).

The steps proceeds as in the NBC case (although we demonstrate the classAgreement functionality for evaluation the classifier). You can get details on the method by querying the help files.
